<font color="#FF0000">MY THOUGHTS</font><br>
<tt>Sun Nov  2 22:41:04 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
John,<br><br>
Your response is yet another example of how much wisdom exists on these pages.<br><br>
I will repeat, one more time, what I said on another thread. I would have never have know how important it was for me, and I believe our country to be in Vietnam, had I not been there.  I cannot escape that thought.  Who knows what my thoughts and opinions would be if I didn't agree to help my friend in the fall of 1966.  There was never an intention for me to go; it was to help him from not going overseas.  Time does not change what is true.<br><br>
Vietnam, to me, was part of the chess game we refer to as the Cold War.  Intentions are noble and they are self serving -- so are people -- me anyway.<br><br>
I believe now that the Vietnam War was a necessary actiion for our country to take.  I believe that Kennedy and Johnson tried to fight the war on the &quot;cheap.&quot;  Johnson tried negotiation and left office in 1968.  Nixon did the best he could with a bad situation.  I should note that I have been called many things in my life, but never a Republican.  I never voted for Reagan,  but thought his plusses far exceeded his minuses -- once again in my eyes.<br><br>
I think that Diem and Thieu did they best they could under the circumstances.  Their choices were harder than ours.  It should always be remembered that the US Congress cut off aid to the Republic of South Vietnam in 1975.<br><br>
Waging a controversial war in a free society is always difficult.  I recently read that Johnson is quoted as saying that he did not wqnt to use the &quot;bully pulpit&quot; as the presidency is sometimes called to justify our actions with rhetoric.  He remembered what it did to Wilson and other presidents.  Was that a big mistake?  It probably was.  The &quot;other side&quot; did.  To them it was immoral -- but were our actions immoral, or as immoral as the actions of North Vietnam.  I don't think so.<br><br>
I think sometimes that we did the best we could under the circumstances.  Living in a free society necessitates dissension and disagreement.  That, to me, is human nature and what makes the America what it is, a place where many other people want to come to.<br><br>
I've run on -- hate to do that.  There are a lot more thoughts, but I will save them for another time.<br><br>
Paul
